Sysco CFO Joel Grade: Connecting Finance to Customers and the Business







 







Joel Grade






 
Since joining Houston-based Sysco Corp. as a staff auditor in 1996, Joel Grade has not only held a variety of finance positions but has also worked as president of Sysco Canada and as a regional senior vice president of foodservice operations. Those experiences, he says, have shaped his roll-up-your-sleeves view of finance, and informed him on how finance can help drive the company’s growth.
In this conversation with Tom Bendert, principal with Deloitte Consulting LLP, Mr. Grade discusses why he thinks Sysco is well-positioned to build on its 48-year legacy as it continues to work toward improving the customer experience, enhancing associate engagement and achieving financial objectives.
Tom Bendert: Joel, what are the top priorities for Sysco?
Joel Grade: At Sysco’s Investor Day in September 2015, we laid out a three-year strategic plan intended to achieve a gain in operating income of at least $400 million. Halfway through, we are actually outperforming our goals so the new target is $600 million to $650 million. Our strategy is based on several pillars that we refer to as the “5 P’s”— partnership, productivity, products, people and portfolio. Within each of these, we have specific objectives to drive the customer experience and be more productive in everything we do. For example, we have invested in a shared services center that, while still in its early stages, is allowing us to provide more consistent service to our customers while taking transactional work out of the field. Similarly, we are finding ways to better utilize technology to make our sales force more productive, such as eliminating manual order taking and other administrative tasks, so that salespeople can spend more time selling.
Improving productivity across the organization is something we approach very holistically because it is so closely tied to growth. By understanding what we do, where we do it and how we do it, we can gain leverage out of our cost structure and reinvest the savings we achieve into the business to drive growth. Our ultimate aim is to invest in people, technology and process to enhance our customer experience and make our business more competitive and differentiated.
Tom Bendert: What support do you as CFO and your finance team provide in these efforts?
Joel Grade: Part of my responsibility, in conjunction with other team members, is to help increase productivity by determining where we can invest, to both grow our business and drive costs out of our system. One way we do that is by having finance very much integrated into the business. We have people who support the sales function, merchandising, marketing, business technology, supply chain and other areas in order to achieve that. In addition, we have our locations in the field in which there is a regional structure with a finance leader to support the teams in those local markets.
I find people—whether in the supply chain, marketing, sales or some other function—have many great ideas, but to effectively monetize them, finance needs to be closely involved, in order to say, “That makes sense, but have you considered X?” or “What can we also do here?” That’s the expectation I have for my people, to work as part of the solution and to help make sure that we get the most out of the investments we make, whether it’s a marketing campaign, a new customer contract or venturing into a new market segment.
Our finance team is also focused on capital allocation issues—how we might reinvest in the business, return value to shareholders in the form of dividends, pursue M&A, pay down debt and so on.
Tom Bendert: How does M&A fit into Sysco’s growth strategy, and what role does finance play?
Joel Grade: M&A is a key capital allocation priority, and we think of it in three buckets. One is around our core North American business, which has been our primary market; our approach to M&A here is mostly for smaller fold-in-and-tuck-in deals, either to broaden our geographies or to broaden our capabilities and product lines. Our product line is diverse, from mop handles to lobster tails, so we look for companies that have products—and, importantly, expertise—in, say, produce or meat or seafood. I’d call those core-business acquisitions.
The second bucket is around adjacencies; products or services that complement our business, such as hotel amenities. And the third bucket is around international, as geographic expansion is an important part of our overall strategy. Historically, our approach has been to do a couple of larger, transformative deals and then build around them. Last year we acquired the Brakes Group in Europe, and we continue to expand in Latin America and in the Caribbean. Finance is closely involved across the entire M&A process, from analyzing prospective deals to financing the transaction to supporting the integration work, including integrating the acquired company’s finance processes. We also work closely with our investor relations team to represent the transaction to the marketplace and put it in the context of our overall growth story.
Tom Bendert: Given the expanding scope of what Sysco sells and to whom, how do you keep pace with customers’ expectations?
Joel Grade: Sysco has always been a customer-centric organization—­it’s ingrained in our DNA, and we are always evolving our capabilities. We realize that every market we operate in has unique needs, whether it’s Miami, Florida or Lyon, France. We’ve made technology investments that enable us to serve our customers much more consistently and efficiently.
We also have a team of finance people who support our merchandising organization, specifically around category management. For example, they provide analytics and related support to help determine the opportunities and pitfalls in different product categories. Although the finance team doesn’t make decisions on specific products, they partner with merchandising colleagues to identify opportunities and risks. They also assess opportunities and trends where finance can provide insight.
Tom Bendert: How does your international expansion impact the composition of your investor base?
Joel Grade: Sysco has always had a very international shareholder base­—it’s about 16% now, which is well above average for what we regard as our peer group. Our key shareholder base is long-term strategic investors. There are some U.S. shareholders who fit that description, and that profile is also represented strongly in the European investor base, and also in Asia, which is relatively small for us now. During and after our acquisition of Brakes, we spent time in Europe developing our story and getting our name out in places that have long-term, high-quality investors. So as Sysco’s world has expanded, we have changed and evolved our investor outreach to include relatively frequent interaction with international investors.
When I think about communicating with investors, regardless of market, I think it’s all about being clear and consistent, transparent and balanced, and giving people the color behind the business so that they understand the full context. I believe in talking about the “good, the bad and the ugly,” focusing on the “why” of what you’re doing, and holding yourselves accountable.
Tom Bendert: How does your goal to embed finance into the business influence your talent development strategy?
Joel Grade: We don’t have an ivory-tower culture in finance; rather, we have people who combine financial skills with a desire to really participate in the business. And so we need sharp, innovative analytical people who aren’t afraid to get their hands dirty.
For people who want to move around and gain diverse experiences, we provide opportunities to do that, and providing opportunities is at the core of how I think about talent development. For example, somebody can come here and get experience working hand-in-hand with sales, with merchandising, with supply chain and also gain experience in our field organization, among other areas. We don’t have a formal rotation program, but we do create detailed individual development plans. We also emphasize coaching and try to help people to maximize their performance and meet their career goals.
Tom Bendert: You have a strong operations background and a long tenure at Sysco. How has that shaped your approach to the CFO role?
Joel Grade: Both of those factors are fundamental to how I operate. A number of the people who serve as “market presidents” have worked for me at some point. That has helped me build up credibility, which can be helpful when reaching out into the field organization and influencing a decision. They know that I understand our markets and how our customers think. When you’ve been out in the warehouses talking to night and day staff, when you’ve spent time with the drivers and local suppliers and customers, you gain a broader perspective. It’s part of what helps finance be an active participant in helping drive our business. My philosophy is, we are all in sales, we are all in operations, and we all ultimately own this organization, so don’t be a bystander.
Editor’s note: This article is part of an ongoing series of interviews with CEOs, CFOs and other executives. Mr. Grade’s participation in this article is solely for educational purposes based on his knowledge of the subject, and the views expressed by him are solely his own. This article should not be deemed or construed to be for the purpose of soliciting business for Sysco Corp., nor does Deloitte advocate or endorse the services or products provided by Sysco.





